      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Which tour is better for a first-time visitor to Yogyakarta?</h3>
        <p>If you have only one evening, the Yogyakarta Historical and Food Tour packs more context into fewer hours. If you have a full day, the cooking class gives you a deeper cultural understanding through hands-on cooking.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I do both tours in the same day?</h3>
        <p>Yes. The cooking class runs in the morning (around 6:30 AM to 11 AM) and the historical tour starts in the late afternoon (around 5:30 PM). You have a few hours between them to rest or explore. Just do not eat lunch between the two.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Are the tours suitable for vegetarians?</h3>
        <p>The cooking class is more flexible because you cook your own meal and can request vegetarian adjustments. The historical tour focuses on meat-heavy street food and is harder to adapt.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much walking is involved in each tour?</h3>
        <p>The cooking class involves a short walk through the market (about 500 metres) and then you are in the kitchen. The historical tour covers about two kilometres over uneven lanes and market floors. Wear comfortable shoes for the historical tour.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do I need to book in advance?</h3>
        <p>Yes for both. The cooking class caps at six to eight people and sells out. The historical tour also has limited group sizes. Book at least a few days ahead onlin.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the best season for these tours?</h3>
        <p>Both tours run year-round. The dry season (May to September) offers the most comfortable evenings for the historical tour. The cooking class market visit is covered, so it works in any weather. In the wet season (November to March), afternoon rain is common but both tours are scheduled to avoid it.</p>
      </div>
